SpNote.note:
This list of bright imaging standards has been taken from www.jach.hawaii.edu/JACpublic/UKIRT/astronomy/calib/10_20stds.html and you should refer to this page for magnitudes.
These observations follow a standard technique for N and Q band point source imaging on a 2-d array, with a chop throw of 15 arcseconds North-South and offsets (ABBA) perpendicular to the chop angle.
SpNote.title: About N and Q Band Imaging Standards
About N and Q band telluric standards
SpNote.note:
This list of N and Q band telluric standards for broad band Michelle spectroscopy has been taken from the list at www.jach.hawaii.edu/JACpublic/UKIRT/astronomy/calib/ratio_std.html.
Stars later than K0 do not have a N band observation as these are not suitable for 10 micron ratioing due to SiO bands.
The observations are set up to use the 2-pixel wide slit and a position angle of 0.0, i.e., the slit is North-South. N band observations are centered at 10.5 microns, the Q band is centered at 21 microns. Chop throw is 16 arcsecs (which is a multiple of the fast guider super pixels and close to an integer number of Michelle pixels) and is North-South along the slit. Offsets are 8 arcseconds along the slit. If you require different settings, please copy the relevant observation into your area and make the changes there.
There are two observations at the top of the list for calibration observations. For LowN spectroscopy, this includes flats and an arc, but the LowQ calibration observation only includes flats, as sky lines should be used for Q band wavelength calibration. The calibration observations should be run before taking data on the standard star, as the DR recipe in each standard star observation expects a flat to have been taken. If you decide to take a spectrum of the standard star first, you should change the DR recipe to "STANDARD_STAR_NOFLAT".
If you change the standard star settings in the Michelle instrument component, please make sure you also similarly change the Michelle instrument component in the calibration observations.
